metadata.name: Reconnaissance #234
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #452
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: The Modern Prometheus #71
metadata.description:
We are collections of the various people we've met. Each one of us is different but also is different to everyone we meet. We construct ourselves out of others' identities, traumas, shared experiences, and stories we tell ourselves (and have told about us). 

Like the resurrected monster, we live and learn through the way others react to us. We each yearn to be loved, and lash out against things trying to harm us. Without empathy, we're all the protagonists of our own story, and the monster is someone else's.

Like Dr. Victor Frankenstein, we experiment and bring life to things that we can't fully comprehend. We also cannot understand the full extent of the unintended consequences of our actions.

Whether NFTs will be a net positive or negative to society is far from decided, and, like these creatures you're minting, you may find beauty or horror when all is said and done.

metadata.name: Rehash 10000 #274
metadata.description:
This project was supposed to be released in celebration of fxhash reaching 10,000 projects since its inception, but it's hard to celebrate when war breaks out and innocent people fear for their lives. Please go ahead and mint as many iterations as you like for free. If you feel the art is worth more than 0 tez, you are welcome to donate to the Tezos fund to support our Ukrainian friends (KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx).

Each mint combines 5 of my previous 14 fxhash projects into a drug-induced distorted vision of life in the Metaverse. This artwork is fully generative and was entirely hand-coded in 5333 lines of plain JavaScript code. Forever limited to 500 editions on the Tezos blockchain. London, February 2022.

metadata.name: Totalistic Cellular Automata #465
metadata.description:
Totalistic Cellular Automata is a work celebrating my appreciation and love for 1D Cellular Automata. In this piece there are many different rules and rulesets which dictate how the cells will behave. Totalistic cellular automata is a type of cellular automata where the total or average values of cells in a neighborhood are what the rules depend on.

Clicking the image continues or pauses the generation.

There are 4 dimension sizes, 4 possible states, 52 possible rulesets, and 55 colorways. 

This generator was inspired by the works and discoveries of Stephen Wolfram and “RGB Elementary Cellular Automata” by Ciphrd which will always have a special place in my heart.

JohnWow(2022)
